A backend developer has implemented caching for a Java Spring Boot application that serves user profile data. The application is used by both a customer-facing web portal (200,000 users) and an internal admin panel (50 admin users).

```java
@Service
public class UserProfileService {

    @Cacheable(value = "userProfiles", key = "#userId")
    public UserProfile getUserProfile(Long userId) {
        UserProfile profile = userRepository.findById(userId)
            .orElseThrow(() -> new UserNotFoundException(userId));

        // Enrich with permissions based on the calling context
        if (SecurityContext.getCurrentUser().hasRole("ADMIN")) {
            profile.setAuditLog(auditService.getRecentActions(userId));
            profile.setInternalNotes(noteService.getAdminNotes(userId));
            profile.setLoginHistory(authService.getLoginHistory(userId));
        }

        return profile;
    }

    // Cache configuration: TTL = 1 hour, max entries = 10,000
}
```

The caching behavior observed in testing:
1. Admin views user #12345 → full profile with audit log, notes, and login history is cached
2. Regular user #12345 views their own profile → receives the cached version, which includes admin-only fields (audit log, notes, login history)
3. After cache eviction (1 hour), if a regular user views first, the admin then gets a profile without admin fields until the next cache refresh

The development team's position: "The admin fields are not security-sensitive — they're audit data. And the cache dramatically reduced database load from 2,000 queries/minute to 200. We can fix this in the next sprint."

The security team's position: "Login history and internal notes are PII and should never be exposed to non-admin users, regardless of sensitivity level.

